The third Title treats oi the lex Aquilia, arr early statute which practically contains the whole ol the law of lnjury to property, damnum iniuria datum. The peculiarity ol this Delict is that mere negligence is sufficient to render one liable to its penalties: ‘non minus quarn ex dolo ex culpa quisque hac lege tenetur! What amounts to negligence in this connection is clearly shown bya series of illustrations. The lex Aquilia contained three chapters, the second oi which was obsolete under Justinian. The first dealt with the killing ol slaves and certain domesticated animab, and imposed a penalty os the highest value such slave or animal had borne at any time within the year imme· diately preceding. The third related to almost every other kind of damage to property: its penalty was such property's highest value within the last thirty days before the wrong was done.
